13. Restore Files (Stop Screwing Around with Reset)
Bring back a file without nuking everything
git restore file.js
git restore --staged file.js
restore → replaces file with last committed version
--staged → removes from staging (undo git add)

Use when: you messed up ONE file, not the whole repo

Examples:

You edited config incorrectly → restore just that file
You accidentally staged secrets → unstage without losing changes
⏮️ 14. Checkout Old State (Time Travel Without Damage)
git checkout <commit_hash>
Moves you to a past commit (detached HEAD)

Reality: You’re NOT on a branch here. Changes can disappear if you don’t branch.

Examples:

Debug a bug introduced 3 commits ago
Compare old vs new logic manually

👉 If you want to keep changes:

git switch -c fix-old-bug
🔀 15. Merge vs Rebase (Stop Confusing These)
Merge
git merge feature
Keeps history messy but safe
Rebase
git rebase main
Rewrites history, cleaner

Brutal truth:

Merge = safe for teams
Rebase = safe only locally

Examples:

Team project → use merge
Solo feature cleanup → use rebase
🧠 16. Fix Merge Conflicts (The Right Way)

When conflict happens:

git status

Then:

# edit files manually
git add .
git commit

If rebasing:

git rebase --continue

Abort if needed:

git merge --abort
git rebase --abort

Examples:

Same function edited in 2 branches
Config file changed differently
📦 17. Tagging (Version Control Like a Pro)
git tag v1.0
git push origin v1.0
Marks a release point

Examples:

Before deploying production build
Mark stable version before risky changes
🧪 18. Bisect (Find Bugs Like a Machine)
git bisect start
git bisect bad
git bisect good <commit>

Git will binary search the bad commit.

Examples:

Bug appeared but you don’t know where
Performance dropped suddenly

👉 This saves HOURS of manual checking.

🧷 19. Revert (Safe Undo for Shared Branches)
git revert HEAD
Creates new commit that undoes changes
DOES NOT rewrite history

Brutal rule:

Use revert instead of reset on shared branches

Examples:

You broke production → revert safely
Wrong logic pushed → undo without force push
🔍 20. Blame (Who Wrote This Garbage?)
git blame file.js
Shows who changed each line

Examples:

Track who introduced bug
Understand why weird logic exists
🧱 21. Squash Commits (Clean Your Mess)
git rebase -i HEAD~3


Then change:

pick → squash

Use when: your history looks like garbage

Examples:

“fix typo”, “fix again”, “final fix” → squash
Clean PR before pushing
🧳 22. Worktrees (Underrated Weapon)
git worktree add ../feature-branch feature
Work on multiple branches simultaneously in different folders

Examples:

Hotfix + feature development at same time
Compare two branches side-by-side
📡 23. Fetch Specific Branch (Not Everything)
git fetch origin feature-branch

Examples:

You only care about one branch
Avoid pulling entire repo updates
🪓 24. Delete Local Branch (Clean Up Junk)
git branch -d branch_name
git branch -D branch_name
-d safe delete
-D force delete

Examples:

Feature merged → delete branch
Dead experiment → remove it
🧨 25. Reset Soft vs Mixed vs Hard (You Only Know 1/3)
git reset --soft HEAD~1
git reset --mixed HEAD~1
git reset --hard HEAD~1
Differences:
soft → keep changes staged
mixed → keep changes unstaged
hard → delete everything

Examples:

Fix commit message → soft
Rework code → mixed
Kill everything → hard
🧯 26. Reflog (Your Last Lifeline)
git reflog

Then:

git reset --hard <hash>

This saves you when you mess up badly.

Examples:

You ran reset --hard accidentally
You lost a branch
